  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Shelter and NFI Climitization Assistance for Conflict Affected Households</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The military offensive to recapture Hawiga city and surrounding areas from the control of Islamic State (IS) began in September 2017. The area - primarily in Kirkuk governorate but reaching into Erbil, Ninewa, and Salah al-Din governorates - has been under the control of IS since June 2014. Currently nearly 700,000 people are displaced in Kirkuk and Salah al Din governorates (IOM DTM Sept 2017). Many have been protractedly displaced for some years now, have exhausted their assets and are forced to employ negative coping mechanisms. Since the Hawiga offensive began there has been increased displacement from Hawiga district into surrounding areas. There are also many extremely vulnerable households who have remained in Hawiga district, rather than becoming displaced. 

This project will directly contribute to the shelter cluster objective as part of the IHPF Hawiga Reserve Allocation Strategy to address the emergency shelter and NFI needs of newly displaced individuals in accessible areas. Activities will be carried out in line with agreed priority locations in order to meet most urgent identified need. The planned geographic locations of NFI support may be in Kirkuk, Erbil, Ninewa and Salah al Din governorates, prioritizing Kirkuk camps and emergency sites when possible and appropriate. Over the last two months Kirkuk has seen increasing numbers of newly displaced arrivals from Hawiga district. This project will provide NFIs to 1,734 households (approximately 8,436 individuals) in Kirkuk, Erbil, Ninewa, and Salah al Din governorates, prioritizing climatisation items in order to support households through the harsh seasonal conditions. Items provided will include household climatisation items, clothing, shoes and shelter winterization NFI. Resources will be prioritised initially to respond to identified needs and gaps in Kirkuk camps that have received new arrivals from Hawiga.Vulnerable households who have recently returned to newly accessible areas in Kirkuk governorate, and highly vulnerable households who have remained during the protracted occupation by IS and recent military offensive in Hawiga district may also be targeted based on identified need, security and accessibility.</narrative>
  </description>
